<paragraph blockId="20.[160,1157,905,1070]" box="[160,409,905,931]" pageId="20" pageNumber="285">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,409,905,931]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="285">External morphology</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[160,1157,905,1070]" pageId="20" pageNumber="285">Body elongate, narrow, background colour light orange with whitish-blue electric marks. Oral tentacles present a whitish blue line connecting apical part with base of rhinophores. Rhinophores conical, slightly annulated, whitish-yellow apically. Cerata abundant, smooth, base red, tops orange, blue and yellow.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="285" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="20.[160,1155,1125,1255]" box="[160,252,1125,1151]" pageId="20" pageNumber="285">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,252,1125,1151]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="285">Ecology</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[160,1155,1125,1255]" pageId="20" pageNumber="285">
This species has a very broad diet (
<bibRefCitation author="Betti F &amp; Cattaneo-Vietti R &amp; Bava S" box="[580,769,1161,1186]" pageId="20" pageNumber="285" pagination="1 - 4" refId="ref18245" refString="Betti F, Cattaneo-Vietti R, Bava S. 2015. Northernmost record of Godiva quadricolor (Gastropoda: Nudibranchia) in the SCI &quot; fondali Noli - Bergeggi &quot; (Ligurian Sea). Mar Biodivers Rec. 8: 1 - 4. doi: 10.1017 / S 1755267215000032." type="journal article" year="2015">Betti et al. 2015</bibRefCitation>
), and is commonly found eating anemones (e.g. the genera 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Risso" authorityYear="1826" box="[491,604,1196,1221]" class="Anthozoa" family="Actiniidae" genus="Anemonia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Actiniaria" pageId="20" pageNumber="285" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[491,604,1196,1221]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="285">Anemonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Gosse" authorityYear="1858" box="[671,760,1196,1221]" class="Anthozoa" family="Aiptasiidae" genus="Aiptasia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Actiniaria" pageId="20" pageNumber="285" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[671,760,1196,1221]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="285">Aiptasia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), worms (e.g. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1767" box="[933,1013,1196,1221]" class="Polychaeta" family="Sabellidae" genus="Sabella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="20" pageNumber="285" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[933,1013,1196,1221]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="285">Sabella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), and other heterobranchs such as 
<taxonomicName authority="(Delle Chiaje, 1841)" baseAuthorityName="Delle Chiaje" baseAuthorityYear="1841" box="[420,867,1230,1255]" class="Gastropoda" family="Aeolidiidae" genus="Spurilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Nudibranchia" pageId="20" pageNumber="285" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="neapolitana">
<emphasis box="[420,640,1230,1255]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="285">Spurilla neapolitana</emphasis>
(Delle Chiaje, 1841)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="285" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="20.[160,1156,1311,1476]" box="[160,300,1311,1337]" pageId="20" pageNumber="285">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,300,1311,1337]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="285">Distribution</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[160,1156,1311,1476]" pageId="20" pageNumber="285">
This is an invasive species originally from 
<collectingCountry box="[634,772,1347,1372]" name="South Africa" pageId="20" pageNumber="285">South Africa</collectingCountry>
and the Pacific Sea [e.g. 
<collectingCountry box="[1058,1155,1347,1372]" name="Australia" pageId="20" pageNumber="285">Australia</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Nimbs MJ &amp; Smith SD" box="[166,450,1381,1406]" pageId="20" pageNumber="285" pagination="44 - 113" refId="ref21181" refString="Nimbs MJ, Smith SD. 2017. An illustrated inventory of the sea slugs of New South Wales, Australia (Gastropoda: Heterobranchia). Proc R Soc Vic. 128: 44 - 113. doi: 10.1071 / RS 16011." type="journal article" year="2017">Nimbs and Smith 2017</bibRefCitation>
), Hawaii (
<bibRefCitation author="Gosliner TM" box="[575,742,1381,1406]" pageId="20" pageNumber="285" pagination="37 - 77" refId="ref19877" refString="Gosliner TM. 1980 [&quot; 1979 &quot;]. The systematics of the Aeolidiacea (Nudibranchia: Mollusca) of the Hawaiian Islands, with descriptions of two new species. Pacific Sci. 33: 37 - 77." type="journal article" year="1980">Gosliner 1980</bibRefCitation>
), now found in 
<collectingCountry box="[953,1004,1381,1406]" name="Italy" pageId="20" pageNumber="285">Italy</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1021,1101,1381,1406]" name="France" pageId="20" pageNumber="285">France</collectingCountry>
, the Mediterranean Spanish coast: Andalucía (
<bibRefCitation author="Zenetos A &amp; Macic V &amp; Jaklin A &amp; Lipej L &amp; Poursanidis D &amp; Cattaneo-Vietti R &amp; Beqiraj S &amp; Betti F &amp; Poloniato D &amp; Kashta L" box="[630,852,1416,1441]" pageId="20" pageNumber="285" pagination="1239 - 1255" refId="ref23116" refString="Zenetos A, Macic V, Jaklin A, Lipej L, Poursanidis D, Cattaneo-Vietti R, Beqiraj S, Betti F, Poloniato D, Kashta L 2016. Adriatic ' opisthobranchs' (Gastropoda, Heterobranchia): shedding light on biodiversity issues. Mar Ecol. 37: 1239 - 1255. doi: 10.1111 / maec. 12306." type="journal article" year="2016">Zenetos et al. 2016</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Gerovasileiou V &amp; Akel EHK &amp; Akyol O &amp; Alongi G &amp; Azevedo F" box="[867,1148,1416,1441]" pageId="20" pageNumber="285" pagination="355 - 384" refId="ref19830" refString="Gerovasileiou V, Akel EHK, Akyol O, Alongi G, Azevedo F, et al. 2017. New Mediterranean Biodiversity Records (July 2017). Mediterr Mar Sci. 18: 355 - 384. doi: 10.12681 / mms. 13771." type="journal article" year="2017">Gerovasileiou et al. 2017</bibRefCitation>
) and Catalonia (this study).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="285" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="20.[160,1155,1532,1627]" box="[160,262,1532,1558]" pageId="20" pageNumber="285">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,262,1532,1558]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="285">Remarks</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[160,1155,1532,1627]" pageId="20" pageNumber="285">
This species is a large facelinid with a very characteristic colour pattern, making it difficult to misidentify. In the Étang de Thau, 
<collectingCountry box="[575,652,1602,1627]" name="France" pageId="20" pageNumber="285">France</collectingCountry>
, the species is very abundant during spring.]
</paragraph>
